You're on the right track with the tables you've designed. For a solid e-commerce order system, you typically need **at least two core tables**, which you already have:

---

## ‚úÖ Your Current Tables:

### `order`

Stores general information about each order.

| Column             | Type          | Description                                                  |
| ------------------ | ------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| `id`               | PK            | Unique identifier for the order                              |
| `user_id`          | FK ‚Üí users    | The user who placed the order                                |
| `status`           | ENUM / string | e.g., 'pending', 'paid', 'shipped', 'delivered', 'cancelled' |
| `amount`           | decimal       | Total order amount                                           |
| `delivery_date`    | date/datetime | Scheduled or actual delivery date                            |
| `payment_method`   | string/ENUM   | e.g., 'card', 'paypal', 'COD'                                |
| `shipping_address` | text or FK    | Full shipping address or a reference to an `addresses` table |

---

### `order_items`

Details for each product in an order.

| Column       | Type         | Description                                              |
| ------------ | ------------ | -------------------------------------------------------- |
| `order_id`   | FK ‚Üí order   | Which order this item belongs to                         |
| `product_id` | FK ‚Üí product | Product being purchased                                  |
| `quantity`   | int          | Number of units ordered                                  |
| `price`      | decimal      | Price per unit at time of purchase                       |
| `notes`      | text (opt)   | Optional note for the product (e.g. size, customization) |

---

## ‚úÖ Optional but Recommended Tables

Depending on how robust you want your system to be, consider the following additions:

---

### üè∑ `order_status_history` *(Optional)*

Track status changes over time for auditing or tracking purposes.

| Column       | Type            | Description                    |
| ------------ | --------------- | ------------------------------ |
| `id`         | PK              | Unique ID                      |
| `order_id`   | FK ‚Üí order      | Which order                    |
| `status`     | ENUM/string     | New status                     |
| `changed_at` | timestamp       | When the status was updated    |
| `changed_by` | FK ‚Üí user/admin | Who updated it (if applicable) |

---

### üí≥ `payments` *(Optional but useful if payment is more complex)*

Track payment attempts, methods, and confirmation.

| Column           | Type        | Description              |
| ---------------- | ----------- | ------------------------ |
| `id`             | PK          | Unique ID                |
| `order_id`       | FK ‚Üí order  | Associated order         |
| `payment_method` | ENUM        | Card, PayPal, etc.       |
| `amount`         | decimal     | Paid amount              |
| `status`         | ENUM/string | success, failed, pending |
| `transaction_id` | string      | From payment gateway     |
| `paid_at`        | timestamp   | When payment succeeded   |

---

### üì¶ `shipping` *(If you want to separate it out)*

If you want to track shipping provider and logistics info.

| Column            | Type       | Description           |
| ----------------- | ---------- | --------------------- |
| `id`              | PK         | Unique ID             |
| `order_id`        | FK ‚Üí order | Associated order      |
| `provider`        | string     | e.g., UPS, FedEx      |
| `tracking_number` | string     | Shipment tracking     |
| `shipped_at`      | timestamp  | When order shipped    |
| `delivered_at`    | timestamp  | When it was delivered |

---

### üè† `addresses` *(If users have multiple addresses)*

Instead of saving full addresses in the `order` table, normalize it.

| Column                                                      | Type      | Description        |
| ----------------------------------------------------------- | --------- | ------------------ |
| `id`                                                        | PK        | Address ID         |
| `user_id`                                                   | FK ‚Üí user | Whose address      |
| `line1`, `line2`, `city`, `state`, `postal_code`, `country` | strings   | Address details    |
| `type`                                                      | ENUM      | shipping / billing |

---

## TL;DR ‚Äì Your Minimum Setup ‚úÖ

If you're just getting started, you can simplify and **keep only**:

* `order`
* `order_items`

And optionally later add:

* `order_status_history`
* `payments`
* `shipping`
* `addresses`

Would you like me to help write the SQL schema for any of these?
